com.apriori.collections

Class FibonacciHeapOrderedQueue<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • com.apriori.collections.FibonacciHeapOrderedQueue<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of element in the queue
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    MeldableOrderedQueue<E,FibonacciHeapOrderedQueue<? extends E>>, OrderedQueue<E>, Serializable, Cloneable, Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, Queue<E>

    public class FibonacciHeapOrderedQueue<E>
extends AbstractCollection<E>
implements MeldableOrderedQueue<E,FibonacciHeapOrderedQueue<? extends E>>, Serializable, Cloneable
    A priority queue that supports merging of two queues and is backed by a Fibonacci heap. Insertion, merging, and finding the minimum (or maximum) value all run in constant time. Removing the minimum element runs in amortized logarithmic time (amortized because remove operations incur heap maintenance work, which will be logarithmic incremental work when averaged over many remove operations but can cause worst case linear performance for a single operation). Other operations, like finding or removing arbitrary elements run in linear time.

    This collection supports all optional operations of the Queue interface. Removal of an element fetched by an iterator runs in logarithmic time worst case, constant time best case.

    Iteration order for this collection is not defined other than the minimum element in the queue will be retrieved first.

    Since the OrderedQueue interface does not include the "decrease key" operation, this implementation does not offer it. Removing an arbitrary element from a Fibonacci heap would usually be done using the "decrease key" operation followed by a "remove minimum". But arbitrary removal of elements in this heap is only done via its iterator(), and that standard remove algorithm would make it very difficult to continue with iteration and still guarantee that each element is traversed once and only once. So a modified remove operation is used instead:

    1. Remove the node from its list of siblings.
    2. Splice the removed node's children (if any) into its place in the list of siblings.
    3. Update the parent's pointer to children so it is pointing at the smallest child (now that its children have been augmented with grandchildren, from the removed child).
    4. Decrement the sub-tree node count for the parent node and all ancestor nodes, up to a root. If the decreased count falls below a threshold, also decrement the node's order.
    This revised removal algorithm means that we don't need to keep track of a "mark" on each node. Also, since we only do removals during iteration, and the iterator maintains a stack that implicitly identifies the path to the current node, we do not need to keep track of back pointers to nodes' parents. Instead, the parent can be found by examining the iteration stack.

      • mergeFrom

        public boolean mergeFrom(FibonacciHeapOrderedQueue<? extends E> other)
        Description copied from interface: MeldableOrderedQueue
        Merges the specified queue into this queue. The other queue will be empty when this operation completes and this queue will have the union of its own prior contents and those of the specified queue.

        This is effectively the same as the following:

         MeldablePriorityQueue<T> queue1, queue2;
 // merge queue2 into queue1
 queue1.addAll(queue2);
 queue2.clear();
        The main difference is that this specialized method can perform the merge in constant time (possibly amortized constant time). Without this method, such an operation would likely instead take linear or O(n log n) time.
        Specified by:
        mergeFrom in interface MeldableOrderedQueue<E,FibonacciHeapOrderedQueue<? extends E>>
        Parameters:
        other - the queue whose contents are merged into this queue
        Returns:
        true if both queues were modified as a result; false if the specified queue was empty
